```latex
\documentclass{book}
\usepackage{hyperref}

\title{My Book}
\author{John Doe}
\date{\today}

\begin{document}
\maketitle

\tableofcontents

\chapter{Introduction}
Some text here.

\chapter{Chapter 1}
More text here.

\section{Section 1.1}
Even more text here.

\section{Section 1.2}
And even more text here.

\section{Section 1.3}
But even more text here!

\backmatter

\bibliographystyle{apa}
\bibliography{references}

\end{document}
```

In this example, we first include the `book` class and the `hyperref` package to enable automatic generation of bookmarks for the table of contents. Then we define the title, author, and date of the document using the `\title`, `\author`, and `\date` commands, respectively. Next, we generate the table of contents using `\tableofcontents`, which automatically lists all the headings encountered in the document with their corresponding page numbers.

After the table of contents, we start the main body of the document, which can consist of chapters, sections, and subsections, just like any other LaTeX document. We use the `\chapter`, `\section`, and `\subsection` commands to create headings that will be included in the table of contents.

Finally, we use the `\backmatter` command to indicate that we are shifting to the back matter of the document, which can include appendices, bibliographies, and other references. We define the bibliography style and include a bibliography using `\bibliographystyle` and `\bibliography`, respectively.

I hope this example helps you generate automatic tables of contents in your LaTeX document!

To draw a chessboard using the FEN notation in LaTeX, you can use the 'chessboard' package and its 'chessboard' environment. First, download the package from the following link:

<https://www.ctan.org/pkg/chessboard>

Once you have downloaded and installed the package, you can use the following code:
```latex
\documentclass{article}
\usepackage{chessboard}

\begin{document}
\settocdepth{subsection}
\tableofcontents

\section{FEN Notation}

\setlength\boardwidth{7em}
\setlength\boardoffset{0em}
%% Define the table row height
\setlength\board{1em}

%% Define the starting position of the pieces
\POSitions{StartPosition}{%
<<<START>>> <><-<NORTH>><<><-<NORTH>><-<EAST>><<-<NORTH>><<><-<EAST>>>>><<><<-<SOUTH>><<><<-<WEST>>>><<
}}

\begin{chessboard}
    \setpieces{\bullet\circ}
    \postion{StartPosition}
\end{chessboard}

\end{document}
```
Adjust the 'boardwidth', 'boardoffset', and 'board' settings to suit your preferences. You can also define your own piece symbols by updating the 'setpieces' command. For example, instead of using 'bullet' and 'circ' for white and black pieces, you could use '*' and 'o' respectively.

In the code above, the 'START' string represents the FEN notation you want to use. Replace it with your desired FEN notation, ensuring that the layout of the pieces corresponds to the FEN notation symbol and location. Finally, compile the file to see the chessboard with the specified starting position using the given FEN notation. The result should look like this:

